data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code for your `BackgroundProcessor`.

## Pattern Analysis

Your code has **three** thread-abort patterns:

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Exception as control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

Additionally, `GetNextItem()` "may block" — a `CancellationToken` must be threaded through so the blocked call can wake up.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted.
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException handler.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — OperationCanceledException does not
                // auto-rethrow, so the finally block runs normally and the
                // loop condition exits naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();   // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully.
        // Join replaces the old Sleep+Abort pattern and actually waits
        // for thread exit rather than guessing with a fixed delay.
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## What Changed in `GetNextItem`

Your original comment says `GetNextItem()` may block. You **must** update it to accept and honor the token — otherwise cancellation stalls until it unblocks on its own:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt it
private Item GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// AFTER — wakes up immediately when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
// BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken) throws
// OperationCanceledException when the token fires.
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep` or `WaitHandle.WaitOne` internally, replace those too:

```csharp
// Thread.Sleep — not cancellable
Thread.Sleep(5000);
// Replace with:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000); // returns early if cancelled

// WaitHandle.WaitOne — not cancellable
_signal.WaitOne();
// Replace with:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle });
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing the token to blocking calls** | Cancellation is *cooperative* — if `GetNextItem()` blocks without checking the token, `Stop()` hangs until it unblocks on its own. This is the #1 migration mistake. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` holds timer and callback resources. Always `Dispose()` it. The migrated code implements `IDisposable` for this reason. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to only catch *your* cancellation — not one from an unrelated token deeper in the call stack. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort` (which injected an exception anywhere), cooperative cancellation only fires at checkpoints. If `ProcessItem()` is long-running, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside it at regular intervals. |

## Behavioral Difference from the Original

In .NET Framework, `Thread.Abort` could interrupt the thread *mid-statement* — even inside `ProcessItem`. With cooperative cancellation, `ProcessItem` runs to completion (or to the next checkpoint). If you need mid-operation cancellation, thread the token through `ProcessItem` and check it between steps:

```csharp
private void ProcessItem(Item item, CancellationToken token)
{
    StepOne(item);
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    StepTwo(item);
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    StepThree(item);
}
```
